[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] A high-level representation of a session with an SSH server.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] This class wraps `Transport`, `Channel`, and `SFTPClient` to take care of most aspects of authenticating and opening channels.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] You may pass in explicit overrides for authentication and server host key checking.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] The default mechanism is to try to use local key files or an SSH agent (if one is running).
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] Instances of this class may be used as context managers.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] Load host keys from a system (read-only) file.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] Host keys read with this method will not be saved back by `save_host_keys`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] This method can be called multiple times.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] Each new set of host keys will be merged with the existing set (new replacing old if there are conflicts).
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] If `filename` is left as `None`, an attempt will be made to read keys from the user’s local “known hosts” file, as used by OpenSSH, and no exception will be raised if the file can’t be read.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] Load host keys from a local host-key file.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] Host keys read with this method will be checked after keys loaded via `load_system_host_keys`, but will be saved back by `save_host_keys` (so they can be modified).
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] The missing host key policy `AutoAddPolicy` adds keys to this set and saves them, when connecting to a previously-unknown server.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] When automatically saving, the last hostname is used.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] Only the host keys loaded with `load_host_keys` (plus any added directly) will be saved – not any host keys loaded with `load_system_host_keys`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] This can be used to examine the local host keys or change them.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] the local host keys as a `HostKeys` object.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] The default is `"paramiko.transport"` but it can be set to anything you want.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] Set policy to use when connecting to servers without a known host key.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] Connect to an SSH server and authenticate to it.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] The server’s host key is checked against the system host keys (see `load_system_host_keys`) and any local host keys (`load_host_keys`).
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] If the server’s hostname is not found in either set of host keys, the missing host key policy is used (see `set_missing_host_key_policy`).
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] The default policy is to reject the key and raise an `SSHException`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] If a private key requires a password to unlock it, and a password is passed in, that password will be used to attempt to unlock the key.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] `AuthResult` if `auth_strategy` is non-`None`; otherwise, returns `None`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] Changed in version 1.15: Added the `banner_timeout` argument.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] Changed in version 2.4: Added the `passphrase` argument.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] Changed in version 2.6: Added the `disabled_algorithms` argument.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] Changed in version 2.12: Added the `transport_factory` argument.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] Changed in version 3.2: Added the `auth_strategy` argument.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] Close this SSHClient and its underlying `Transport`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] This should be called anytime you are done using the client object.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] Paramiko registers garbage collection hooks that will try to automatically close connections for you, but this is not presently reliable.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] Failure to explicitly close your client after use may lead to end-of-process hangs!
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] A new `Channel` is opened and the requested command is executed.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] The command’s input and output streams are returned as Python `file`-like objects representing stdin, stdout, and stderr.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] Changed in version 1.10: Added the `get_pty` kwarg.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] Start an interactive shell session on the SSH server.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] A new `Channel` is opened and connected to a pseudo-terminal using the requested terminal type and size.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] Return the underlying `Transport` object for this SSH connection.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] This can be used to perform lower-level tasks, like opening specific kinds of channels.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] Interface for defining the policy that `SSHClient` should use when the SSH server’s hostname is not in either the system host keys or the application’s keys.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] Pre-made classes implement policies for automatically adding the key to the application’s `HostKeys` object (`AutoAddPolicy`), and for automatically rejecting the key (`RejectPolicy`).
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] This function may be used to ask the user to verify the key, for example.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] Called when an `SSHClient` receives a server key for a server that isn’t in either the system or local `HostKeys` object.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] To reject, raised an exception (which will be passed to the calling application).
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] Policy for automatically adding the hostname and new host key to the local `HostKeys` object, and saving it.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] Policy for automatically rejecting the unknown hostname & key.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-client] Policy for logging a Python-style warning for an unknown host key, but accepting it.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] An alias for `SFTPClient` for backwards compatibility.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Used to open an SFTP session across an open SSH `Transport` and perform remote file operations.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Create an SFTP client from an existing `Channel`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The channel should already have requested the `"sftp"` subsystem.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] An alternate way to create an SFTP client context is by using `from_transport`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Change the “current directory” of this SFTP session.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Since SFTP doesn’t really have the concept of a current working directory, this is emulated by Paramiko.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Once you use this method to set a working directory, all operations on this `SFTPClient` object will be relative to that path.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] You can pass in `None` to stop using a current working directory.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Change the mode (permissions) of a file.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The permissions are unix-style and identical to those used by Python’s `os.chmod` function.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Change the owner (`uid`) and group (`gid`) of a file.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] As with Python’s `os.chown` function, you must pass both arguments, so if you only want to change one, use `stat` first to retrieve the current owner and group.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Close the SFTP session and its underlying channel.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The arguments are the same as for Python’s built-in `python:file` (aka `open`).
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] A file-like object is returned, which closely mimics the behavior of a normal Python file object, including the ability to be used as a context manager.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The mode indicates how the file is to be opened: `'r'` for reading, `'w'` for writing (truncating an existing file), `'a'` for appending, `'r+'` for reading/writing, `'w+'` for reading/writing (truncating an existing file), `'a+'` for reading/appending.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The Python `'b'` flag is ignored, since SSH treats all files as binary.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The `'U'` flag is supported in a compatible way.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Since 1.5.2, an `'x'` flag indicates that the operation should only succeed if the file was created and did not previously exist.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] This has no direct mapping to Python’s file flags, but is commonly known as the `O_EXCL` flag in posix.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The file will be buffered in standard Python style by default, but can be altered with the `bufsize` parameter.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] `<=0` turns off buffering, `1` uses line buffering, and any number greater than 1 (`>1`) uses that specific buffer size.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] `IOError` – if the file could not be opened.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Create an SFTP client channel from an open `Transport`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Setting the window and packet sizes might affect the transfer speed.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The default settings in the `Transport` class are the same as in OpenSSH and should work adequately for both files transfers and interactive sessions.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Changed in version 1.15: Added the `window_size` and `max_packet_size` arguments.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Copy a remote file (`remotepath`) from the SFTP server to the local host as `localpath`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Any exception raised by operations will be passed through.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] This method is primarily provided as a convenience.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Changed in version 2.8: Added the `prefetch` keyword argument.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Changed in version 3.3: Added `max_concurrent_prefetch_requests`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Return the underlying `Channel` object for this SFTP session.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] This might be useful for doing things like setting a timeout on the channel.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Return the “current working directory” for this SFTP session, as emulated by Paramiko.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] If no directory has been set with `chdir`, this method will return `None`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Copy a remote file (`remotepath`) from the SFTP server and write to an open file or file-like object, `fl`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Return a list containing the names of the entries in the given `path`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] It does not include the special entries `'.'` and `'..'` even if they are present in the folder.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] This method is meant to mirror `os.listdir` as closely as possible.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] For a list of full `SFTPAttributes` objects, see `listdir_attr`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Return a list containing `SFTPAttributes` objects corresponding to files in the given `path`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The returned `SFTPAttributes` objects will each have an additional field: `longname`, which may contain a formatted string of the file’s attributes, in unix format.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The content of this string will probably depend on the SFTP server implementation.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] See the API docs for `listdir_attr` for overall details.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] This function adds one more kwarg on top of `listdir_attr`: `read_aheads`, an integer controlling how many `SSH_FXP_READDIR` requests are made to the server.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Retrieve information about a file on the remote system, without following symbolic links (shortcuts).
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] This otherwise behaves exactly the same as `stat`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Create a folder (directory) named `path` with numeric mode `mode`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Where it is used, the current umask value is first masked out.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Return the normalized path (on the server) of a given path.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] This can be used to quickly resolve symbolic links or determine what the server is considering to be the “current folder” (by passing `'.'` as `path`).
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Rename a file or folder from `oldpath` to `newpath`, following posix conventions.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Copy a local file (`localpath`) to the SFTP server as `remotepath`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The SFTP operations use pipelining for speed.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Changed in version 1.7.4: `callback` and rich attribute return value added.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Changed in version 1.7.7: `confirm` param added.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Copy the contents of an open file object (`fl`) to the SFTP server as `remotepath`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] an `SFTPAttributes` object containing attributes about the given file.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Return the target of a symbolic link (shortcut).
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The result may be either an absolute or relative pathname.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] This only works on files; for removing folders (directories), use `rmdir`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Rename a file or folder from `oldpath` to `newpath`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] This method implements ‘standard’ SFTP `RENAME` behavior; those seeking the OpenSSH “POSIX rename” extension behavior should use `posix_rename`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Retrieve information about a file on the remote system.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The return value is an object whose attributes correspond to the attributes of Python’s `stat` structure as returned by `os.stat`, except that it contains fewer fields.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] An SFTP server may return as much or as little info as it wants, so the results may vary from server to server.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Unlike a Python `stat` object, the result may not be accessed as a tuple.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] This is mostly due to the author’s slack factor.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The fields supported are: `st_mode`, `st_size`, `st_uid`, `st_gid`, `st_atime`, and `st_mtime`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Create a symbolic link to the `source` path at `destination`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Change the size of the file specified by `path`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] This usually extends or shrinks the size of the file, just like the `truncate` method on Python file objects.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Set the access and modified times of the file specified by `path`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] If `times` is `None`, then the file’s access and modified times are set to the current time.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Otherwise, `times` must be a 2-tuple of numbers, of the form `(atime, mtime)`, which is used to set the access and modified times, respectively.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] This bizarre API is mimicked from Python for the sake of consistency – I apologize.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Since this is a `SubsystemHandler`, it can be (and is meant to be) set as the handler for `"sftp"` requests.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Use `Transport.set_subsystem_handler` to activate this class.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The constructor for SFTPServer is meant to be called from within the `Transport` as a subsystem handler.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] `server` and any additional parameters or keyword parameters are passed from the original call to `Transport.set_subsystem_handler`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Convert an errno value (as from an `OSError` or `IOError`) into a standard SFTP result code.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] This is a convenience function for trapping exceptions in server code and returning an appropriate result.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] an `int` SFTP error code like `SFTP_NO_SUCH_FILE`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Perform any cleanup at the end of a subsystem.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The default implementation just closes the channel.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Change a file’s attributes on the local filesystem.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The contents of `attr` are used to change the permissions, owner, group ownership, and/or modification & access time of the file, depending on which attributes are present in `attr`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] This is meant to be a handy helper function for translating SFTP file requests into local file operations.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Process an ssh subsystem in server mode.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] This method is called on a new object (and in a new thread) for each subsystem request.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] It is assumed that all subsystem logic will take place here, and when the subsystem is finished, this method will return.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] After this method returns, the channel is closed.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The combination of `transport` and `channel` are unique; this handler corresponds to exactly one `Channel` on one `Transport`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] It is the responsibility of this method to exit if the underlying `Transport` is closed.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] This can be done by checking `Transport.is_active` or noticing an EOF on the `Channel`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] If this method loops forever without checking for this case, your Python interpreter may refuse to exit because this thread will still be running.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Representation of the attributes of a file (or proxied file) for SFTP in client or server mode.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Because SFTP allows flags to have other arbitrary named attributes, these are stored in a dict named `attr`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Occasionally, the filename is also stored, in `filename`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Create a new (empty) SFTPAttributes object.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Create an `SFTPAttributes` object from an existing `stat` object (an object returned by `os.stat`).
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] new `SFTPAttributes` object with the same attribute fields.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Proxy object for a file on the remote server, in client mode SFTP.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Instances of this class may be used as context managers in the same way that built-in Python file objects are.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Ask the server for a hash of a section of this file.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] This can be used to verify a successful upload or download, or for various rsync-like operations.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The file is hashed from `offset`, for `length` bytes.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] If `length` is 0, the remainder of the file is hashed.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Thus, if both `offset` and `length` are zero, the entire file is hashed.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Normally, `block_size` will be 0 (the default), and this method will return a byte string representing the requested hash (for example, a string of length 16 for MD5, or 20 for SHA-1).
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] If a non-zero `block_size` is given, each chunk of the file (from `offset` to `offset + length`) of `block_size` bytes is computed as a separate hash.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The hash results are all concatenated and returned as a single string.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The first 20 bytes will be the SHA-1 of the first 512 bytes of the file, and the last 20 bytes will be the SHA-1 of the next 512 bytes.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Many (most?) servers don’t support this extension yet.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Change the mode (permissions) of this file.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Change the owner (`uid`) and group (`gid`) of this file.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] This may do nothing if write buffering is not turned on.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Returns the timeout in seconds (as a `float`) associated with the socket or ssh `Channel` used for this file.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Pre-fetch the remaining contents of this file in anticipation of future `read` calls.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] If reading the entire file, pre-fetching can dramatically improve the download speed by avoiding roundtrip latency.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The file’s contents are incrementally buffered in a background thread.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The prefetched data is stored in a buffer until read via the `read` method.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Once data has been read, it’s removed from the buffer.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The data may be read in a random order (using `seek`); chunks of the buffer that haven’t been read will continue to be buffered.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Changed in version 1.16.0: The `file_size` parameter was added (with no default value).
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Changed in version 1.16.1: The `file_size` parameter was made optional for backwards compatibility.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Changed in version 3.3: Added `max_concurrent_requests`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Read at most `size` bytes from the file (less if we hit the end of the file first).
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] If the `size` argument is negative or omitted, read all the remaining data in the file.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] `'b'` mode flag is ignored (`self.FLAG_BINARY` in `self._flags`), because SSH treats all files as binary, since we have no idea what encoding the file is in, or even if the file is text data.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] If `False`, `read` will raise an exception.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Read up to `len(buff)` bytes into `bytearray` *buff* and return the number of bytes read.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] A trailing newline character is kept in the string (but may be absent when a file ends with an incomplete line).
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] If the size argument is present and non-negative, it is a maximum byte count (including the trailing newline) and an incomplete line may be returned.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] An empty string is returned only when EOF is encountered immediately.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Unlike stdio’s `fgets`, the returned string contains null characters (`'\0'`) if they occurred in the input.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] next line of the file, or an empty string if the end of the file has been reached.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Read all remaining lines using `readline` and return them as a list.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] If the optional `sizehint` argument is present, instead of reading up to EOF, whole lines totalling approximately sizehint bytes (possibly after rounding up to an internal buffer size) are read.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Read a set of blocks from the file by (offset, length).
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] This is more efficient than doing a series of `seek` and `read` calls, since the prefetch machinery is used to retrieve all the requested blocks at once.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Check if the file supports random access.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] `True` if the file supports random access.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Turn on/off the pipelining of write operations to this file.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] When pipelining is on, paramiko won’t wait for the server response after each write operation.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Instead, they’re collected as they come in.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] At the first non-write operation (including `close`), all remaining server responses are collected.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] This means that if there was an error with one of your later writes, an exception might be thrown from within `close` instead of `write`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Set blocking or non-blocking mode on the underiying socket or ssh `Channel`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Set a timeout on read/write operations on the underlying socket or ssh `Channel`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Retrieve information about this file from the remote system.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] This is exactly like `SFTPClient.stat`, except that it operates on an already-open file.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] an `SFTPAttributes` object containing attributes about this file.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] This may not be accurate or useful if the underlying file doesn’t support random access, or was opened in append mode.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] This usually extends or shrinks the size of the file, just like the `truncate()` method on Python file objects.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Set the access and modified times of this file.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] If `False`, `write` will raise an exception.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] If write buffering is on (`bufsize` was specified and non-zero), some or all of the data may not actually be written yet.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Write a sequence of strings to the file.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The sequence can be any iterable object producing strings, typically a list of strings.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] This is a deprecated file interface that predates Python iterator support.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Abstraction of an SFTP file handle (for server mode).
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Abstract object representing a handle to an open file (or folder) in an SFTP server implementation.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Each handle has a string representation used by the client to refer to the underlying file.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Server implementations can (and should) subclass SFTPHandle to implement features of a file handle, like `stat` or `chattr`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Create a new file handle representing a local file being served over SFTP.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] If `flags` is passed in, it’s used to determine if the file is open in append mode.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The `attr` object will contain only those fields provided by the client in its request, so you should check for the presence of fields before using them.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] When a client closes a file, this method is called on the handle.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Normally you would use this method to close the underlying OS level file object(s).
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The default implementation checks for attributes on `self` named `readfile` and/or `writefile`, and if either or both are present, their `close()` methods are called.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] This means that if you are using the default implementations of `read` and `write`, this method’s default implementation should be fine also.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Read up to `length` bytes from this file, starting at position `offset`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The offset may be a Python long, since SFTP allows it to be 64 bits.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] If the end of the file has been reached, this method may return an empty string to signify EOF, or it may also return `SFTP_EOF`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The default implementation checks for an attribute on `self` named `readfile`, and if present, performs the read operation on the Python file-like object found there.
