[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Extending the file past its original end is expected.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Unlike Python’s normal `write()` methods, this method cannot do a partial write: it must write all of `data` or else return an error.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The default implementation checks for an attribute on `self` named `writefile`, and if present, performs the write operation on the Python file-like object found there.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The attribute is named differently from `readfile` to make it easy to implement read-only (or write-only) files, but if both attributes are present, they should refer to the same file.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] An interface to override for SFTP server support.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] This class defines an interface for controlling the behavior of paramiko when using the `SFTPServer` subsystem to provide an SFTP server.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Methods on this class are called from the SFTP session’s thread, so you can block as long as necessary without affecting other sessions (even other SFTP sessions).
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] However, raising an exception will usually cause the SFTP session to abruptly end, so you will usually want to catch exceptions and return an appropriate error code.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] All paths are in string form instead of unicode because not all SFTP clients & servers obey the requirement that paths be encoded in UTF-8.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Create a new SFTPServerInterface object.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] This method does nothing by default and is meant to be overridden by subclasses.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Return the canonical form of a path on the server.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] For example, if the server’s home folder is `/home/foo`, the path `"../betty"` would be canonicalized to `"/home/betty"`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Note the obvious security issues: if you’re serving files only from a specific folder, you probably don’t want this method to reveal path names outside that folder.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] You may find the Python methods in `os.path` useful, especially `os.path.normpath` and `os.path.realpath`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The default implementation returns `os.path.normpath('/' + path)`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Return a list of files within a given folder.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The `path` will use posix notation (`"/"` separates folder names) and may be an absolute or relative path.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The list of files is expected to be a list of `SFTPAttributes` objects, which are similar in structure to the objects returned by `os.stat`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] In addition, each object should have its `filename` field filled in, since this is important to a directory listing and not normally present in `os.stat` results.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The method `SFTPAttributes.from_stat` will usually do what you want.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] In case of an error, you should return one of the `SFTP_*` error codes, such as `SFTP_PERMISSION_DENIED`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] a list of the files in the given folder, using `SFTPAttributes` objects.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] You should normalize the given `path` first (see the `os.path` module) and check appropriate permissions before returning the list of files.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Be careful of malicious clients attempting to use relative paths to escape restricted folders, if you’re doing a direct translation from the SFTP server path to your local filesystem.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Return an `SFTPAttributes` object for a path on the server, or an error code.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] If your server supports symbolic links (also known as “aliases”), you should not follow them – instead, you should return data on the symlink or alias itself.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] an `SFTPAttributes` object for the given file, or an SFTP error code (like `SFTP_PERMISSION_DENIED`).
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Create a new directory with the given attributes.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The `attr` object may be considered a “hint” and ignored.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The `attr` object will contain only those fields provided by the client in its request, so you should use `hasattr` to check for the presence of fields before using them.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] In some cases, the `attr` object may be completely empty.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] an SFTP error code `int` like `SFTP_OK`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Open a file on the server and create a handle for future operations on that file.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] On success, a new object subclassed from `SFTPHandle` should be returned.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] This handle will be used for future operations on the file (read, write, etc).
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] On failure, an error code such as `SFTP_PERMISSION_DENIED` should be returned.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The `attr` object contains requested attributes of the file if it has to be created.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Some or all attribute fields may be missing if the client didn’t specify them.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The SFTP protocol defines all files to be in “binary” mode.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] There is no equivalent to Python’s “text” mode.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Rename (or move) a file, following posix conventions.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] If newpath already exists, it will be overwritten.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Return the target of a symbolic link (or shortcut) on the server.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] If the specified path doesn’t refer to a symbolic link, an error should be returned.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] the target `str` path of the symbolic link, or an error code like `SFTP_NO_SUCH_FILE`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] You should return an error if a file with the same name as `newpath` already exists.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The `path` should refer to an existing, empty folder – otherwise this method should return an error.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The SFTP server session has just ended, either cleanly or via an exception.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] This method is meant to be overridden to perform any necessary cleanup before this `SFTPServerInterface` object is destroyed.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] The SFTP server session has just started.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] This method is meant to be overridden to perform any necessary setup before handling callbacks from SFTP operations.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] If your server supports symbolic links (also known as “aliases”), you should follow them.
[src:paramiko-ssh/api-sftp] Create a symbolic link on the server, as new pathname `path`, with `target_path` as the target of the link.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] OpenSSH started as a fork of the free SSH program developed by Tatu Ylönen; later versions of Ylönen's SSH were proprietary software offered by SSH Communications Security.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] OpenSSH was first released in 1999 and is currently developed as part of the OpenBSD operating system.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] OpenSSH is not a single computer program, but rather a suite of programs that serve as alternatives to unencrypted protocols like Telnet and FTP.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] OpenSSH is integrated into several operating systems, namely Microsoft Windows, macOS and most Linux operating systems, while the portable version is available as a package in other systems.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] OpenBSD Secure Shell was developed by OpenBSD developers as an alternative to the original SSH software by Tatu Ylönen, which is now proprietary software.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] Although source code is available for the original SSH, various restrictions are imposed on its use and distribution.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] OpenSSH was created as a fork of Björn Grönvall's OSSH that itself was a fork of Tatu Ylönen's original free SSH 1.2.12 release, which was the last one having a license suitable for forking.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] The OpenSSH developers claim that their application is more secure than the original, due to their policy of producing clean and audited code and because it is released under the BSD license, the open-source license to which the word *open* in the name refers.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] The first portable release was made in October 1999.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] On 19 October 2015, Microsoft announced that OpenSSH will be natively supported on Microsoft Windows and accessible through PowerShell, releasing an early implementation and making the code publicly available.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] OpenSSH-based client and server programs have been included in Windows 10 since version 1803.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] The SSH client and key agent are enabled and available by default, and the SSH server is an optional Feature-on-Demand.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] In October 2019 protection for private keys at rest in RAM against speculation and memory side-channel attacks were added in OpenSSH 8.1.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] OpenSSH is developed as part of the OpenBSD operating system.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] Rather than including changes for other operating systems directly into OpenSSH, a separate portability infrastructure is maintained by the OpenSSH Portability Team, and "portable releases" are made periodically.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] This infrastructure is substantial, partly because OpenSSH is required to perform authentication, a capability that has many varying implementations.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] This model is also used for other OpenBSD projects such as OpenNTPD.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] The server makes use of authentication methods native to the host operating system; this can include using the BSD Authentication system or pluggable authentication modules (PAM) to enable additional authentication through methods such as one-time passwords.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] However, this occasionally has side effects: when using PAM with OpenSSH, it must be run as root, as root privileges are typically required to operate PAM.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] OpenSSH versions after 3.7 (16 September 2003) allow PAM to be disabled at run-time, so regular users can run sshd instances.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] On OpenBSD, OpenSSH uses a dedicated sshd user by default to drop privileges and perform privilege separation in accordance with the principle of least privilege, applied throughout the operating system including the Xenocara X server.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] For example, an X Window System tunnel may be created automatically when using OpenSSH to connect to a remote host, and other protocols, such as HTTP and VNC, may be forwarded easily.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] In addition, some third-party software includes support for tunnelling over SSH.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] These include DistCC, CVS, rsync, and Fetchmail.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] On some operating systems, remote file systems can be mounted over SSH using tools such as sshfs (using FUSE).
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] An *ad hoc* SOCKS proxy server may be created using OpenSSH.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] This allows more flexible proxying than is possible with ordinary port forwarding.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] Beginning with version 4.3, OpenSSH implements an OSI layer 2/3 tun-based VPN.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] This is the most flexible of OpenSSH's tunnelling capabilities, allowing applications to transparently access remote network resources without modifications to make use of SOCKS.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] Before version 5.2 of OpenSSH, it was possible for an attacker to recover up to 14 bits of plaintext with a success probability of 2−14.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] The vulnerability was related to the CBC encryption mode.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] The AES CTR mode and arcfour ciphers are not vulnerable to this attack.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] A local privilege escalation vulnerability existed in OpenSSH 6.8 to 6.9 (CVE-2015-6565) due to world-writable (622) TTY devices, which was believed to be a denial of service vulnerability.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] With the use of the TIOCSTI ioctl, it was possible for authenticated users to inject characters into other users terminals and execute arbitrary commands on Linux.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] This applies to versions 5.4 (released on 8 March 2010) to 7.1 of the OpenSSH client, and was fixed in OpenSSH 7.1p2, released on 14 January 2016.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] CVE numbers associated to this vulnerability are CVE-2016-0777 (information leak) and CVE-2016-0778 (buffer overflow).
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] On March 29, 2024, a serious supply chain attack on XZ Utils was reported, indirectly targeting the OpenSSH server (sshd) running on Linux.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] The OpenSSH code is not directly affected, as the backdoor is caused by the dependencies on liblzma via libsystemd that could be applied by various Linux distributions.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] On July 1, 2024, the RegreSSHion security vulnerability was disclosed, which could enable a remote attacker to cause OpenSSH to execute arbitrary code and gain full root access.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] It was inadvertently introduced in prior OpenSSH version 8.5p1 in October 2020, and was patched following version 9.8/9.8p1.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] He proposed that OpenSSH change its name in order to avoid a lawsuit, a suggestion that developers resisted.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] OpenSSH developer Damien Miller replied urging Ylönen to reconsider, arguing that "SSH" had long since been a generic trademark.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] At the time, "SSH", "Secure Shell" and "ssh" had appeared in documents proposing the protocol as an open standard.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] Without marking these within the proposal as registered trademarks, Ylönen ran the risk of relinquishing all exclusive rights to the name as a means of describing the protocol.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] Improper use of a trademark, or allowing others to use a trademark incorrectly, results in the trademark becoming a generic term, like Aspirin, which opens the mark to use by others.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] After study of the USPTO trademark database, many online pundits opined that the term "ssh" was not trademarked, merely the logo using the lower case letters "ssh".
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] In addition, the six years between the company's creation and the time when it began to defend its trademark, and that only OpenSSH was receiving threats of legal repercussions, weighed against the trademark's validity.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] Both developers of OpenSSH and Ylönen himself were members of the IETF working group developing the new standard; after several meetings this group denied Ylönen's request to rename the protocol, citing concerns that it would set a bad precedent for other trademark claims against the IETF.
[src:paramiko-ssh/openssh] The participants argued that both "Secure Shell" and "SSH" were generic terms and could not be trademarks.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] Public key algorithms are fundamental security primitives in modern cryptosystems, including applications and protocols that offer assurance of the confidentiality and authenticity of electronic communications and data storage.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] They underpin numerous Internet standards, such as Transport Layer Security (TLS), SSH, S/MIME, and PGP.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] Compared to symmetric cryptography, public-key cryptography can be too slow for many purposes, so these protocols often combine symmetric cryptography with public-key cryptography in hybrid cryptosystems.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] Before the mid-1970s, all cipher systems used symmetric key algorithms, in which the same cryptographic key is used with the underlying algorithm by both the sender and the recipient, who must both keep the key secret.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] Of necessity, the key in every such system had to be exchanged between the communicating parties in some secure way prior to any use of the system – for instance, via a secure channel.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] This requirement is never trivial and very rapidly becomes unmanageable as the number of participants increases, when secure channels are not available, or when (as is sensible cryptographic practice) keys are frequently changed.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] In particular, if messages are meant to be secure from other users, a separate key is required for each possible pair of users.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] By contrast, in a public-key cryptosystem, the public keys can be disseminated widely and openly, and only the corresponding private keys need be kept secret.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] For example, a software publisher can create a signature key pair and include the public key in software installed on computers.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] Later, the publisher can distribute an update to the software signed using the private key, and any computer receiving an update can confirm it is genuine by verifying the signature using the public key.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] As long as the software publisher keeps the private key secret, even if a forger can distribute malicious updates to computers, they cannot convince the computers that any malicious updates are genuine.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] For example, a journalist can publish the public key of an encryption key pair on a website so that sources can send secret messages to the news organization in ciphertext.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] Only the journalist who knows the corresponding private key can decrypt the ciphertexts to obtain the sources' messages—an eavesdropper reading email on its way to the journalist cannot decrypt the ciphertexts.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] However, public-key encryption does not conceal metadata like what computer a source used to send a message, when they sent it, or how long it is.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] Public-key encryption on its own also does not tell the recipient anything about who sent a message—it just conceals the content of the message.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] Applications built on public-key cryptography include authenticating web servers with TLS, digital cash, password-authenticated key agreement, authenticating and concealing email content with OpenPGP or S/MIME, and time-stamping services and non-repudiation protocols.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] One important issue is confidence or proof that a particular public key is authentic, i.e., that it is correct and belongs to the person or entity claimed, and has not been tampered with or replaced by some (perhaps malicious) third party.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] A public key infrastructure (PKI), in which one or more third parties, known as certificate authorities, certify ownership of key pairs.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] This implies that the PKI system (software, hardware, and management) can be trusted by all involved.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] A web of trust decentralizes authentication by using individual endorsements of links between a user and their public key.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] PGP uses this approach, in addition to lookup in the domain name system (DNS).
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] The DKIM system for digitally signing emails also uses this approach.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] PGP, SSH, and the SSL/TLS family of schemes use this procedure; they are thus called hybrid cryptosystems.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] As with all security-related systems, there are various potential weaknesses in public-key cryptography.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] Aside from poor choice of an asymmetric key algorithm (there are few that are widely regarded as satisfactory) or too short a key length, the chief security risk is that the private key of a pair becomes known.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] All security of messages, authentication, etc., encrypted with this private key will then be lost.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] This is commonly mitigated (such as in recent TLS schemes) by using Forward secrecy capable schemes that generate an ephemeral set of keys during the communication which must also be known for the communication to be compromised.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] Additionally, with the advent of quantum computing, many asymmetric key algorithms are considered vulnerable to attacks, and new quantum-resistant schemes are being developed to overcome the problem.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] Beyond algorithmic or key-length weaknesses, some studies have noted risks when private key control is delegated to third parties.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] Research on Uruguay’s implementation of Public Key Infrastructure under Law 18.600 found that centralized key custody by Trust Service Providers (TSPs) may weaken the principle of private-key secrecy, increasing exposure to man-in-the-middle attacks and raising concerns about legal non-repudiation.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] All public key schemes are in theory susceptible to a "brute-force key search attack".
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] However, such an attack is impractical if the amount of computation needed to succeed – termed the "work factor" by Claude Shannon – is out of reach of all potential attackers.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] In many cases, the work factor can be increased by simply choosing a longer key.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] But other algorithms may inherently have much lower work factors, making resistance to a brute-force attack (e.g., from longer keys) irrelevant.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] Some special and specific algorithms have been developed to aid in attacking some public key encryption algorithms; both RSA and ElGamal encryption have known attacks that are much faster than the brute-force approach.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] None of these are sufficiently improved to be actually practical, however.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] Major weaknesses have been found for several formerly promising asymmetric key algorithms.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] The "knapsack packing" algorithm was found to be insecure after the development of a new attack.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] As with all cryptographic functions, public-key implementations may be vulnerable to side-channel attacks that exploit information leakage to simplify the search for a secret key.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] These are often independent of the algorithm being used.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] Research is underway to both discover, and to protect against, new attacks.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] Another potential security vulnerability in using asymmetric keys is the possibility of a "man-in-the-middle" attack, in which the communication of public keys is intercepted by a third party (the "man in the middle") and then modified to provide different public keys instead.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] Encrypted messages and responses must, in all instances, be intercepted, decrypted, and re-encrypted by the attacker using the correct public keys for the different communication segments so as to avoid suspicion.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] A communication is said to be insecure where data is transmitted in a manner that allows for interception (also called "sniffing").
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] These terms refer to reading the sender's private data in its entirety.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] A communication is particularly unsafe when interceptions can not be prevented or monitored by the sender.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] A man-in-the-middle attack can be difficult to implement due to the complexities of modern security protocols.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] However, the task becomes simpler when a sender is using insecure media such as public networks, the Internet, or wireless communication.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] In these cases an attacker can compromise the communications infrastructure rather than the data itself.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] A hypothetical malicious staff member at an Internet service provider (ISP) might find a man-in-the-middle attack relatively straightforward.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] Capturing the public key would only require searching for the key as it gets sent through the ISP's communications hardware; in properly implemented asymmetric key schemes, this is not a significant risk.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] In some advanced man-in-the-middle attacks, one side of the communication will see the original data while the other will receive a malicious variant.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] Asymmetric man-in-the-middle attacks can prevent users from realizing their connection is compromised.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] This remains so even when one user's data is known to be compromised because the data appears fine to the other user.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] This can lead to confusing disagreements between users such as "it must be on your end!" when neither user is at fault.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] Hence, man-in-the-middle attacks are only fully preventable when the communications infrastructure is physically controlled by one or both parties; such as via a wired route inside the sender's own building.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] In summation, public keys are easier to alter when the communications hardware used by a sender is controlled by an attacker.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] One approach to prevent such attacks involves the use of a public key infrastructure (PKI); a set of roles, policies, and procedures needed to create, manage, distribute, use, store and revoke digital certificates and manage public-key encryption.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] Web browsers, for instance, are supplied with a long list of "self-signed identity certificates" from PKI providers – these are used to check the *bona fides* of the certificate authority and then, in a second step, the certificates of potential communicators.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] An attacker who could subvert one of those certificate authorities into issuing a certificate for a bogus public key could then mount a "man-in-the-middle" attack as easily as if the certificate scheme were not used at all.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] An attacker who penetrates an authority's servers and obtains its store of certificates and keys (public and private) would be able to spoof, masquerade, decrypt, and forge transactions without limit, assuming that they were able to place themselves in the communication stream.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] Despite its theoretical and potential problems, Public key infrastructure is widely used.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] Examples include TLS and its predecessor SSL, which are commonly used to provide security for web browser transactions (for example, most websites utilize TLS for HTTPS).
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] Aside from the resistance to attack of a particular key pair, the security of the certification hierarchy must be considered when deploying public key systems.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] Some certificate authority – usually a purpose-built program running on a server computer – vouches for the identities assigned to specific private keys by producing a digital certificate.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] Public key digital certificates are typically valid for several years at a time, so the associated private keys must be held securely over that time.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] When a private key used for certificate creation higher in the PKI server hierarchy is compromised, or accidentally disclosed, then a "man-in-the-middle attack" is possible, making any subordinate certificate wholly insecure.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] Most of the available public-key encryption software does not conceal metadata in the message header, which might include the identities of the sender and recipient, the sending date, subject field, and the software they use etc.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] Rather, only the body of the message is concealed and can only be decrypted with the private key of the intended recipient.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] This means that a third party could construct quite a detailed model of participants in a communication network, along with the subjects being discussed, even if the message body itself is hidden.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] However, there has been a recent demonstration of messaging with encrypted headers, which obscures the identities of the sender and recipient, and significantly reduces the available metadata to a third party.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] The concept is based around an open repository containing separately encrypted metadata blocks and encrypted messages.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] Only the intended recipient is able to decrypt the metadata block, and having done so they can identify and download their messages and decrypt them.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] Such a messaging system is at present in an experimental phase and not yet deployed.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] Scaling this method would reveal to the third party only the inbox server being used by the recipient and the timestamp of sending and receiving.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] The server could be shared by thousands of users, making social network modelling much more challenging.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] During the early history of cryptography, two parties would rely upon a key that they would exchange by means of a secure, but non-cryptographic, method such as a face-to-face meeting, or a trusted courier.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] This key, which both parties must then keep absolutely secret, could then be used to exchange encrypted messages.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] A number of significant practical difficulties arise with this approach to distributing keys.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] Here he described the relationship of one-way functions to cryptography, and went on to discuss specifically the factorization problem used to create a trapdoor function.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] Ellis, a British cryptographer at the UK Government Communications Headquarters (GCHQ), conceived of the possibility of "non-secret encryption", (now called public key cryptography), but could see no way to implement it.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] In 1973, his colleague Clifford Cocks implemented what has become known as the RSA encryption algorithm, giving a practical method of "non-secret encryption", and in 1974 another GCHQ mathematician and cryptographer, Malcolm J.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] Williamson, developed what is now known as Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] The scheme was also passed to the US's National Security Agency.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] Both organisations had a military focus and only limited computing power was available in any case; the potential of public key cryptography remained unrealised by either organization.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] These discoveries were not publicly acknowledged until the research was declassified by the British government in 1997.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] In 1976, an asymmetric key cryptosystem was published by Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman who, influenced by Ralph Merkle's work on public key distribution, disclosed a method of public key agreement.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] This method of key exchange, which uses exponentiation in a finite field, came to be known as Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] This was the first published practical method for establishing a shared secret-key over an authenticated (but not confidential) communications channel without using a prior shared secret.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] Merkle's "public key-agreement technique" became known as Merkle's Puzzles, and was invented in 1974 and only published in 1978.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] This makes asymmetric encryption a rather new field in cryptography although cryptography itself dates back more than 2,000 years.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] In 1977, a generalization of Cocks's scheme was independently invented by Ron Rivest, Adi Shamir and Leonard Adleman, all then at MIT.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] The latter authors published their work in 1978 in Martin Gardner's Scientific American column, and the algorithm came to be known as RSA, from their initials.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] RSA uses exponentiation modulo a product of two very large primes, to encrypt and decrypt, performing both public key encryption and public key digital signatures.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] Its security is connected to the extreme difficulty of factoring large integers, a problem for which there is no known efficient general technique.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] A description of the algorithm was published in the Mathematical Games column in the August 1977 issue of Scientific American.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] Since the 1970s, a large number and variety of encryption, digital signature, key agreement, and other techniques have been developed, including the Rabin signature, ElGamal encryption, DSA and ECC.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] In addition to the algorithms developed within the open academic and standards communities, several countries have developed national public-key cryptography standards for use within their jurisdictions.
[src:paramiko-ssh/public-key-cryptography] These include SM2 and SM9 (China), GOST R 34.10-2012 (Russia), EC-KCDSA (South Korea), and DSTU 4145 (Ukraine).
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] The **Secure Shell Protocol** (**SSH Protocol**) is a cryptographic network protocol for operating network services securely over an unsecured network.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] Its most notable applications are remote login and command-line execution.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] SSH was designed for Unix-like operating systems as a replacement for Telnet and unsecured remote Unix shell protocols, such as the Berkeley Remote Shell (rsh) and the related rlogin and rexec protocols, which all use insecure, plaintext methods of authentication, such as passwords.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] Secure Shell mitigates this risk through the use of encryption mechanisms that are intended to hide the contents of the transmission from an observer, even if the observer has access to the entire data stream.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] Finnish computer scientist Tatu Ylönen designed SSH in 1995 and provided an implementation in the form of two commands, ssh and slogin, as secure replacements for rsh and rlogin, respectively.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] Subsequent development of the protocol suite proceeded in several developer groups, producing several variants of implementation.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] The protocol specification distinguishes two major versions, referred to as SSH-1 and SSH-2.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] The most commonly implemented software stack is OpenSSH, released in 1999 as open-source software by the OpenBSD developers.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] Implementations are distributed for all types of operating systems in common use, including embedded systems.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] SSH applications are based on a client–server architecture, connecting an SSH client instance with an SSH server.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] SSH uses public-key cryptography to authenticate the remote computer and allow it to authenticate the user, if necessary.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] SSH may be used in several methodologies.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] In the simplest manner, both ends of a communication channel use automatically generated public-private key pairs to encrypt a network connection, and then use a password to authenticate the user.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] When the public-private key pair is generated by the user manually, the authentication is essentially performed when the key pair is created, and a session may then be opened automatically without a password prompt.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] In this scenario, the public key is placed on all computers that must allow access to the owner of the matching private key, which the owner keeps private.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] While authentication is based on the private key, the key is never transferred through the network during authentication.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] SSH only verifies that the same person offering the public key also owns the matching private key.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] In all versions of SSH, it is important to verify unknown public keys, i.e., associate the public keys with identities, before accepting them as valid.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] Accepting an attacker's public key without validation will authorize an unauthorized attacker as a valid user.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] On Unix-like systems, the list of authorized public keys is typically stored in the home directory of the user that is allowed to log in remotely, in the file `~/.ssh/authorized_keys`.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] This file is respected by SSH only if it is not writable by anything apart from the owner and root.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] When the public key is present on the remote end, and the matching private key is present on the local end, typing in the password is no longer required.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] However, for additional security, the private key itself can be locked with a passphrase.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] The private key can also be looked for in standard places, and its full path can be specified as a command-line setting (the option `-i` for ssh).
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] The ssh-keygen utility produces the public and private keys, always in pairs.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] SSH is typically used to log into a remote computer's shell or command-line interface (CLI) and to execute commands on a remote server.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] It also supports mechanisms for tunneling, forwarding of TCP ports and X11 connections and it can be used to transfer files using the associated SSH File Transfer Protocol (SFTP) or Secure Copy Protocol (SCP).
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] An SSH client program is typically used for establishing connections to an SSH daemon, such as sshd, accepting remote connections.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] Both are commonly present on most modern operating systems, including macOS, most distributions of Linux, OpenBSD, FreeBSD, NetBSD, Solaris and OpenVMS.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] Notably, versions of Windows prior to Windows 10 version 1709 do not include SSH by default, but proprietary, freeware and open source versions of various levels of complexity and completeness did and do exist (see Comparison of SSH clients).
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] In 2018 Microsoft began porting the OpenSSH source code to Windows and in Windows 10 version 1709, an official Win32 port of OpenSSH is now available.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] File managers for UNIX-like systems (e.g., Konqueror) can use the FISH protocol to provide a split-pane GUI with drag-and-drop.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] The open source Windows program WinSCP provides similar file management (synchronization, copy, remote delete) capability using PuTTY as a back-end.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] Both WinSCP and PuTTY are available packaged to run directly off a USB drive, without requiring installation on the client machine.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] Crostini on ChromeOS comes with OpenSSH by default.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] Setting up an SSH server in Windows typically involves enabling a feature in the Settings app.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] SSH is important in cloud computing to solve connectivity problems, avoiding the security issues of exposing a cloud-based virtual machine directly on the Internet.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] An SSH tunnel can provide a secure path over the Internet, through a firewall to a virtual machine.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] The IANA has assigned TCP port 22, UDP port 22 and SCTP port 22 for this protocol.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] IANA had listed the standard TCP port 22 for SSH servers as one of the well-known ports as early as 2001.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] SSH can also be run using SCTP rather than TCP as the connection-oriented transport layer protocol.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] In 1995, **Tatu Ylönen**, a researcher at Helsinki University of Technology in Finland designed the first version of the protocol (now called **SSH-1**) prompted by a password-sniffing attack at his university network.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] The goal of SSH was to replace the earlier rlogin, TELNET, FTP and rsh protocols, which did not provide strong authentication nor guarantee confidentiality.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] He chose the port number 22 because it is between `telnet` (port 23) and `ftp` (port 21).
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] Ylönen released his implementation as freeware in July 1995, and the tool quickly gained in popularity.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] Towards the end of 1995, the SSH user base had grown to 20,000 users in fifty countries.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] In December 1995, Ylönen founded SSH Communications Security to market and develop SSH.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] The original version of the SSH software used various pieces of free software, such as GNU libgmp, but later versions released by SSH Communications Security evolved into increasingly proprietary software.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] It was estimated that by 2000, the number of users had grown to 2 million.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] In 2006, after being discussed in a working group named "secsh", a revised version of the SSH protocol, **SSH-2** was adopted as a standard.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] This version offers improved security and new features, but is not compatible with SSH-1.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] For example, it introduces new key-exchange mechanisms like Diffie–Hellman key exchange, improved data integrity checking via message authentication codes like MD5 or SHA-1, which can be negotiated between client and server.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] SSH-2 also adds stronger encryption methods like AES which eventually replaced weaker and compromised ciphers from the previous standard like 3DES.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] New features of SSH-2 include the ability to run any number of shell sessions over a single SSH connection.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] Due to SSH-2's superiority and popularity over SSH-1, some implementations such as libssh (v0.8.0+), Lsh and Dropbear eventually supported only the SSH-2 protocol.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] In January 2006, well after version 2.1 was established, RFC 4253 specified that an SSH server supporting 2.0 as well as prior versions should identify its protocol version as 1.99.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] This version number does not reflect a historical software revision, but a method to identify backward compatibility.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] In 1999, developers, desiring availability of a free software version, restarted software development from the 1.2.12 release of the original SSH program, which was the last released under an open source license.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] This served as a code base for Björn Grönvall's OSSH software.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] Shortly thereafter, OpenBSD developers forked Grönvall's code and created OpenSSH, which shipped with Release 2.6 of OpenBSD.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] From this version, a "portability" branch was formed to port OpenSSH to other operating systems.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] As of 2005, OpenSSH was the single most popular SSH implementation, being the default version in a large number of operating system distributions.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] OpenSSH continues to be maintained and supports the SSH-2 protocol, having expunged SSH-1 support from the codebase in the OpenSSH 7.6 release.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] In 2023, an alternative to traditional SSH was proposed under the name **SSH3** by PhD student François Michel and Professor Olivier Bonaventure and its code has been made open source.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] This new version implements the original SSH Connection Protocol but operates on top of HTTP/3, which runs on QUIC.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] However, the name SSH3 is under discussion, and the project aims to rename itself to a more suitable name.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] The discussion stems from the fact that this new implementation significantly revises the SSH protocol, suggesting it should not be called SSH3.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] SSH is a protocol that can be used for many applications across many platforms including most Unix variants (Linux, the BSDs including Apple's macOS, and Solaris), as well as Microsoft Windows.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] Some of the applications below may require features that are only available or compatible with specific SSH clients or servers.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] For example, using the SSH protocol to implement a VPN is possible, but presently only with the OpenSSH server and client implementation.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] The Secure Shell protocols are used in several file transfer mechanisms.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] This open architecture provides considerable flexibility, allowing the use of SSH for a variety of purposes beyond a secure shell.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] In 1998, a vulnerability was described in SSH 1.5 which allowed the unauthorized insertion of content into an encrypted SSH stream due to insufficient data integrity protection from CRC-32 used in this version of the protocol.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] A fix known as SSH Compensation Attack Detector was introduced into most implementations.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] Many of these updated implementations contained a new integer overflow vulnerability that allowed attackers to execute arbitrary code with the privileges of the SSH daemon, typically root.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] In January 2001 a vulnerability was discovered that allows attackers to modify the last block of an IDEA-encrypted session.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] The same month, another vulnerability was discovered that allowed a malicious server to forward a client authentication to another server.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] Since SSH-1 has inherent design flaws that make it vulnerable, it is now generally considered obsolete and should be avoided by explicitly disabling fallback to SSH-1.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] Most modern servers and clients support SSH-2.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] In November 2008, a theoretical vulnerability was discovered for all versions of SSH which allowed recovery of up to 32 bits of plaintext from a block of ciphertext that was encrypted using what was then the standard default encryption mode, CBC.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] The most straightforward solution is to use CTR, counter mode, instead of CBC mode, since this renders SSH resistant to the attack.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] On December 28, 2014 *Der Spiegel* published classified information leaked by whistleblower Edward Snowden which suggests that the National Security Agency may be able to decrypt some SSH traffic.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] The technical details associated with such a process were not disclosed.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] A 2017 analysis of the CIA hacking tools *BothanSpy* and *Gyrfalcon* suggested that the SSH protocol was not compromised.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] A novel man-in-the-middle attack against most current ssh implementations was discovered in 2023.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] It was named the Terrapin attack by its discoverers.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] However, the risk is mitigated by the requirement to intercept a genuine ssh session, and that the attack is restricted in its scope, fortuitously resulting mostly in failed connections.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] The ssh developers have stated that the major impact of the attack is to degrade the keystroke timing obfuscation features of ssh.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] The vulnerability was fixed in OpenSSH 9.6, but requires both client and server to be upgraded for the fix to be fully effective.
[src:paramiko-ssh/secure-shell] The following RFC publications by the IETF "secsh" working group document SSH-2 as a proposed Internet standard.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] In computing, the **SSH File Transfer Protocol**, also known as **Secure File Transfer Protocol** (**SFTP**), is a network protocol that provides file access, file transfer, and file management over any reliable data stream.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] It was designed by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) as an extension of the Secure Shell protocol (SSH) version 2.0 to provide secure file transfer capabilities, and is seen as a replacement of File Transfer Protocol (FTP) due to superior security.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] The IETF Internet Draft states that, even though this protocol is described in the context of the SSH-2 protocol, it could be used in a number of different applications, such as secure file transfer over Transport Layer Security (TLS) and transfer of management information in VPN applications.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] This protocol assumes that it is run over a secure channel, such as SSH, that the server has already authenticated the client, and that the identity of the client user is available to the protocol.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] Compared to the SCP protocol, which only allows file transfers, the SFTP protocol allows for a range of operations on remote files which make it more like a remote file system protocol.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] An SFTP client's extra capabilities include resuming interrupted transfers, directory listings, and remote file removal.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] There is also support for all UNIX file types, including symbolic links.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] SFTP attempts to be more platform-independent than SCP; with SCP, for instance, the expansion of wildcards specified by the client is up to the server, whereas SFTP's design avoids this problem.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] While SCP is most frequently implemented on Unix platforms, SFTP servers are commonly available on most platforms.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] In SFTP, the file transfer can be easily terminated without terminating a session like other mechanisms do.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] SFTP is not FTP run over SSH, but rather a new protocol designed from the ground up by the IETF SECSH working group.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] It is sometimes confused with Simple File Transfer Protocol.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] The protocol itself does not provide authentication and security; it expects the underlying protocol to secure this.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] SFTP is most often used as subsystem of SSH protocol version 2 implementations, having been designed by the same working group.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] It is possible, however, to run it over SSH-1 (and some implementations support this), or other data streams.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] However, running an SFTP server over SSH-1 is not platform-independent, as SSH-1 does not support the concept of subsystems.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] An SFTP client connecting to an SSH-1 server must be aware of the path to the SFTP server binary on the server side.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] Uploaded files may be associated with their basic attributes, such as time stamps.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] This is an advantage over the common FTP protocol.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) working group "Secsh" that was responsible for the development of the Secure Shell version 2 protocol (RFC 4251) also attempted to draft an extension of that standard for secure file transfer functionality.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] Internet Drafts were created that successively revised the protocol into new versions.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] The software industry began to implement various versions of the protocol before the drafts were standardized.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] As development work progressed, the scope of the Secsh File Transfer project expanded to include file access and file management.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] Eventually, development stalled as some committee members began to view SFTP as a file system protocol, not just a file access or file transfer protocol, which places it beyond the purview of the working group.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] After a seven-year hiatus, in 2013 an attempt was made to restart work on SFTP using the version 3 draft as the baseline.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] Prior to the IETF's involvement, SFTP was a proprietary protocol of SSH Communications Security, designed by Tatu Ylönen with assistance from Sami Lehtinen in 1997.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] Differences between versions 0–2 and version 3 are enumerated upon in section 10 of draft-ietf-secsh-filexfer-02.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] At the outset of the IETF Secure Shell File Transfer project, the Secsh group stated that its objective of SSH File Transfer Protocol was to provide a secure file transfer functionality over any reliable data stream, and to be the standard file transfer protocol for use with the SSH-2 protocol.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] Drafts 00–02 of the IETF Internet Draft define successive revisions of version 3 of the SFTP protocol.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] Drafts 03–04 of the IETF Internet Draft define version 4 of the protocol.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] Draft 05 of the IETF Internet Draft defines version 5 of the protocol.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] Drafts 06–13 of the IETF Internet Draft define successive revisions of version 6 of the protocol.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] The SFTP protocol supports a generic way of indicating extended commands, along with a method of including them in version negotiation.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] An IANA registry is requested, but since the protocol never became an official standard, no such registry has been created.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] The term **SFTP** can also refer to Secure file transfer program, a command-line program that implements the client part of this protocol.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] As an example, the sftp program supplied with OpenSSH implements this.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] Some implementations of the `scp` *program* support both the SFTP and SCP protocols to perform file transfers, depending on what the server supports.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] The scp program supplied with OpenSSH 9.0 and higher defaults to using SFTP.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] Some FTP server implementations implement the SFTP protocol; however, outside of dedicated file servers, SFTP protocol support is usually provided by an SSH server implementation, as it shares the default port of 22 with other SSH services.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] SFTP implementations may include an SSH protocol implementation to leverage integration of SSH connection details with preexisting FTP server access controls, where an alternative SSH server is tolerable or where alternative ports may be used.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] An SSH-2 server which supports subsystems may be leveraged to keep a uniform SSH implementation while enhancing access controls with third party software, at the cost of fine-grained integration with connection details, and SSH-1 compatibility.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] It is difficult to control SFTP transfers on security devices at the network perimeter.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] There are standard tools for logging FTP transactions, like TIS gdev or SUSE FTP proxy, but SFTP is encrypted, rendering traditional proxies ineffective for controlling SFTP traffic.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] There are some tools that implement man-in-the-middle for SSH which also feature SFTP control.
[src:paramiko-ssh/ssh-file-transfer-protocol] Examples of such a tool are Shell Control Box from Balabit and CryptoAuditor from SSH Communications Security (the original developer of the Secure Shell protocol) which provides functions such as SFTP transaction logging and logging of the actual data transmitted on the wire.
